{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"fd8bb260-44df-11ed-82b2-76033370374d","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"f38e5014-9285-42c7-8c5b-45db69719d4e","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Opportunity Costs","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"aa725349-5225-442b-b66b-9394b45c6c4c"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"5cb4cb66-d8ec-4e2a-a48b-eb387caf5abb","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Many projects use a resource that the company already owns. Because the firm does not need to pay cash to acquire this resource for a new project, it is tempting to assume that the resource is available for free. However, in many cases, the resource could provide value for the firm in another opportunity or project. The ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"9f9e9b2c-e578-4ab3-8a51-b0dae777fb97","stage":{"ref":"a6600481-547e-4c1a-bd74-3078b2f3ef4c","sections":[{"ref":"94761b22-37a0-41e7-aede-e877bc7fc6bf","rows":[{"ref":"82599209-5623-4eba-87ef-526d366f1f5b","columns":[{"ref":"185041e6-dc49-42a1-88cd-c7554ea3301c","stageElements":[{"ref":"481ead41-2191-45b8-8a15-a789a7bd17cf","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"5331b505-1691-42c1-a736-0ce22b0e95cc","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"9c632ca9-70b7-4984-a674-a2bed54c15e4","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The value a resource could have provided in its best alternative use.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"opportunity cost","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"24c36233-97b3-4778-993f-c1629b0dd002"},{"object":"text","text":" of using a resource is the value it could have provided in its best alternative use.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"c43b3bf3-9c68-4da2-b0ed-68e0a4e8d23a","stage":{"ref":"fcaaf47e-d9d4-4f72-81c7-04e13547ddc9","sections":[{"ref":"bd75d64b-c411-440b-953b-0af07c55b4ef","rows":[{"ref":"e896f8c8-0337-485a-bc60-bfb855334054","columns":[{"ref":"22714028-ce75-4eb8-80f4-72f0bbf2c979","stageElements":[{"ref":"55ce8041-ab36-4a41-b7b9-5bbe2c7bd635","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"340456d3-68f0-4c76-aa80-9bf41c61587c","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"447525da-a72b-4cac-98c5-b1e8abd64856","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"In ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"40b15412-c71e-45d0-9dd2-2a0472656749","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Chapter 5","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"f2603db0-44e0-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":", we defined the opportunity cost of capital as the rate you could earn on an alternative investment with equivalent risk. We similarly define the opportunity cost of using an existing asset in a project as the cash flow generated by the next-best alternative use for the asset.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"4","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"251b56c8-af6b-4405-9a4c-51726c3e5cfc"},{"object":"text","text":" Because this value is lost when the resource is used by another project, we should include the opportunity cost as an incremental cost of the project. For example, your company may be considering building a retail store on land that it owns. Even though it already owns the land, it is not free to the store project. If it does not put its store on the land, the company could sell the land, for example. This forgone market price for the land is an opportunity cost of the retail store project.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"ef69099a-3ef7-4998-a516-520168d6469d"}]}]}]},{"cssClass":"aside-group  Sidebar_1Aside","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"435cd664-2173-44dc-a8d4-8756a74973a6","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Common Mistake: The Opportunity Cost of an Idle Asset","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"0e76d203-ffc1-4190-9677-ce072b516cb9"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"fe1e8057-c53a-41f4-99df-082d8512a786","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"A common mistake is to conclude that if an asset is currently idle, its opportunity cost is zero. For example, the firm might have a warehouse that is currently empty or a machine that is not being used. Often, the asset may have been idled in anticipation of taking on the new project, and would have otherwise been put to use by the firm. Even if the firm has no alternative use for the asset, the firm could choose to sell or rent the asset. The value obtained from the assetâ€™s alternative use, sale, or rental represents an opportunity cost that must be included as part of the incremental cash flows.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"14b90a52-d3a2-4012-89c9-035136271032"}]}]}]}]},"screenType":"","transitions":{"enter":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""},"exit":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""}},"lockElements":false,"learnerCurrentAttempt":1,"footer":{"buttonText":"Next","buttonIcon":"Arrow","showFooter":false,"showHistoryNavButt